Mark’s contributions to the community are immeasurable; I’m grateful to have known him. My heart is with his family, friends, coworkers and students. My hope is that we can all be a little more loving to each other and a little kinder to our planet—a little more like Mark.

Mark was proud of his students and his work. He’d prep lesson plans and ask for our feedback; he’d introduce us to his student research assistants. We’d bond over our love of Wiseacre beer; he’d brag on his sister Kathy—a talented artist—and wear her designs every chance he got.

The way a person treats service workers says a lot about them. I didn’t have the joy of having Mark as a teacher, but I knew him as a customer for years. Mark knew everyone by name & greeted everyone with a smile. He treated us like family—that’s the kind of person he was. https://t.co/dTE4Ob9H7F

I laughed at the absurdity of his joke, but the truth of it stuck with me. 

I’ve worked in public-facing jobs my whole adult life. I know serving requires listening and leading means embracing feedback. I’m running to bring real, meaningful representation to the people of TN-03.

That night, I told my partner that after years of trying to reach Chuck Fleischmann, I finally met him. His response? “You’ve been calling and emailing him and saying he’s not accessible to regular people. But if you wanted to meet him, all you had to do was run for Congress!”

On Election Day 2020, I drove by Chuck waving his sign outside a voting location, so I pulled over. I walked up to him, introduced myself, and asked if we could get a video together encouraging people to get out and vote (regardless of party). He was hesitant but agreed.

When I first decided to run against Chuck in 2020, I hoped he would have the courage to attend a public forum and debate me. No such luck. One debate host said that Chuck ignored the invitation until declining the day of the event; another got a “maybe,” but Chuck never showed.

Over the years, I’ve received a couple of boilerplate letters from Chuck’s office in response to one or two of my many attempts to reach him. I’m sorry to say that I gave up on his tele-town halls a while ago.

I found that participants of his tele-town halls were screened (and the events were announced with little notice). People asking anything more than a softball question always seemed to be filtered out or disconnected, or time “ran out” before they could ask their questions.

I wanted to let him know my thoughts on upcoming votes, things that mattered to me. Things like ensuring that people held in the custody of Customs & Border Protection are treated humanely, and protecting net neutrality. (I support both; he doesn’t.)

🧵🧵

Other than when I was in college at UTK, I’ve been @RepChuck’s constituent for the nearly 12 years he’s been in office. During that time, I’ve tried to call him, write him, email him, and attend his rare tele-town halls. 

The result? 🦗🦗🦗

Like millions of other American women, I have an IUD. 

I’m running against a 60-year-old man who just voted against my right to make decisions about my own body (like having an IUD).

#VOTE
